<div id="review_3902649511" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3902649511" />
    <a title="TBV" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/98589549-tbv"><img alt="TBV" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1560644618p2/98589549.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3902649511?book_show_action=true">May 02, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="TBV" class="user" itemprop="url" name="TBV" href="/user/show/98589549-tbv">TBV</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/21303061-heaven-has-no-favorites">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/98589549-tbv?shelf=favourites-2021">favourites-2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/98589549-tbv?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/98589549-tbv?shelf=2021">2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/98589549-tbv?shelf=reviewed-2021">reviewed-2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3902649511" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5128798513062339039">A smile, a tear and s - - - i- - - g - - - h as I wipe my eyes...<br/><br/>Shortly after WWII a tubercular woman in a sanatorium in the Swiss mountains meets a racing driver who has stopped by to visit his ex co-driver who is at the facility for a cure. She is introduced to us as Lillian Dunkerque, half Belgian and half Russian. He is simply known as Clerfayt. Lillian, whose prognosis is not good, thinks of the mountains as a prison. To Clerfayt who had been a prisoner of war the Swiss mountains seemed pa</span>
  <span id="freeText5128798513062339039" style="display:none">A smile, a tear and s - - - i- - - g - - - h as I wipe my eyes...<br /><br />Shortly after WWII a tubercular woman in a sanatorium in the Swiss mountains meets a racing driver who has stopped by to visit his ex co-driver who is at the facility for a cure. She is introduced to us as Lillian Dunkerque, half Belgian and half Russian. He is simply known as Clerfayt. Lillian, whose prognosis is not good, thinks of the mountains as a prison. To Clerfayt who had been a prisoner of war the Swiss mountains seemed paradise. He is used to looking Death in the eye.<br /><br />Lillian sees an opportunity to get away from the sanatorium, from the mountains, from sick people (including her close friend Boris Volkov) and from anything to do with her illness. Clerfayt agrees to take her with him to Paris, but it’s no skin off his nose whether she goes or not. Lillian appreciates that he does not mollycoddle her, but treats her normally - Volkov on the other hand is solicitous and unintentionally irritates her. Lillian and Clerfayt both know that death may be just around the corner, and they both try to live life to the full in the here and now. They both want to remain independent and as such travel together, but also spend days apart before continuing their journey. With death on the horizon their priorities have changed, their senses are more acute.<br /><br />And then one of them falls in love. This cannot bode well for either of them.<br /><br />###<br />Erich Maria Remarque takes the reader on an exhilarating ride through the Gotthard tunnel. Here are two extracts from that ride, one at the beginning and one at the end: <i><br />“The train went through a switch and entered the Gotthard tunnel. <br />The walls of the tunnel were damp. Signal lights flew by. After a few moments, Lillian had the feeling that she was riding down a shaft into the center of the earth. The air was stale and old. The noise of the train was re-echoed a thousandfold. In front of her, Lillian saw the two illuminated sedans rocking like two cabins in a boat on the way to Hades. “Will this ever end?” she said.”<br /><br />“The Acheronian roars became a normal rattling, and then ceased altogether. The train stopped in a soft ambiance of gray and gold and mild air. It was the air of life after the vault-like, cold, dead air of the tunnel. It took Lillian a while before she realized that it was raining. She listened to the drops that pattered gently down upon the top of the car; she breathed the soft air, and held her hand out into the rain. Saved, she thought. Cast across the Styx and saved.”</i><br />Considering that they stared death in the face I found these references to Hades and the Styx particularly apt.<br /><br />Perhaps I enjoyed their trip more than they did. They stopped at beautiful places and had good meals and wine, and sometimes I cheered because I had been to the same place. There are some beautiful descriptions, for example when Lillian visits Sainte-Chapelle in Paris and imagines herself bathing in the coloured light from the stained glass windows, or when Clerfayt is on the race track. I was tempted to quote them here, but managed to refrain from doing so.<br /><br />This novel is quite different from the Remarque novels that I read earlier this year, but as usual the writing is beautiful. He is fast becoming a favourite author. <br />###<i><br />“We’re alike, she thought. Both of us have no future. His reaches only to the next race, and mine to the next hemorrhage.”<br /><br />“She did not fear unhappiness; she had lived too long with it and by it. She also did not fear happiness, as did so many of those who thought they were seeking it. What she feared was the prison of mediocrity.”<br /><br />“Past and future hung in a quivering balance, and her first feeling was not of loneliness, but of high, tense solitude. She was taking nothing with her and she did not know where she was going.”<br /><br />“Everything was intensely peaceful and normal; here was an evening without fear and rebellion, and she belonged to it, with the same normality and peacefulness. She had escaped into life. The feeling of it almost choked her.”<br /><br />“Do you see the sky? Morning is coming. Hear the birds? In cities, you only hear them at this time. Nature lovers must go to night clubs, so they can hear thrushes on the way home.”</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="5128798513062339039" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


