    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3843163726" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3843163726" />
    <a title="Ian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/109010813-ian"><img alt="Ian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1613038740p2/109010813.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3843163726?book_show_action=true">Apr 12, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ian" href="/user/show/109010813-ian">Ian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780151399536" href="/book/show/887947.Heaven_Has_No_Favorites">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/109010813-ian?shelf=2021">2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3843163726&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3843163726" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9812059282053660916">How good I think it is: 4.5/5<br/>How much I enjoyed it: 4/5<br/><br/>In a few ways I find that Remarque’s Heaven Has No Favorites has some parallels to Tolstoy’s The Death of Ivan Ilyich—both explore the psyche of the dying, how one claws for meaning and grapples with a life that is ostensibly devoid of it. Set only a few years after the end of the Second World War, Remarque introduces Lillian Dunkerque, a 24 year old patient at a sanatorium in the Swiss Alps, a restless and alluring young woman dying of cons</span>
  <span id="freeText9812059282053660916" style="display:none">How good I think it is: 4.5/5<br />How much I enjoyed it: 4/5<br /><br />In a few ways I find that Remarque’s Heaven Has No Favorites has some parallels to Tolstoy’s The Death of Ivan Ilyich—both explore the psyche of the dying, how one claws for meaning and grapples with a life that is ostensibly devoid of it. Set only a few years after the end of the Second World War, Remarque introduces Lillian Dunkerque, a 24 year old patient at a sanatorium in the Swiss Alps, a restless and alluring young woman dying of consumption whose adult life has consisted entirely of war and illness. Lillian increasingly sees her stay in the idyllic skiing village as a confinement, a monotonous and futile existence in a place frozen in time as the world passes it by. Here she is defined by her illness and is so pampered and policed by the sanatorium staff, who, while effectively extending her life through such persistent and rigorous caretaking, also ensure that she cannot experience the very things that make life worth leading and death worth prolonging. And then she meets Clerfayt, a professional automobile racer who comes to the resort town to visit his former co-driver, Hollman, another resident/inmate at the sanatorium and a friend of Lillian’s. <br /><br />Clerfayt fought in the war and was interned in a concentration camp as a prisoner of war, experiences he tells little of but which are clearly sources of untold and unresolved traumas. Lillian is confounded and infuriated by this—even after having been so near to death and having surely experienced the great yearning and newfound love for life that only the condemned can know, Clerfayt has still chosen to pursue such a reckless existence after rebirth. She finds him even more contemptible upon meeting him and is appalled by how trivially and dismissively he regards the prospect of death, not only with regard to his own life but to the lives of others. And yet she finds she is also morbidly intrigued by his perspective and is pleased by how his frivolous disregard for death allows him to live in the moment and to be the only person she has met in her time at the sanatorium able to treat her as though she were healthy and normal. When Clerfayt leaves for Paris, Lillian comes with him, and shortly after leaving the two begin a tempestuous and ill-fated love affair. <br /><br />The more I consider the relationship between Clerfayt and Lillian, the more I appreciate how it unfolds and how it makes sense that they oscillate between love and resentment so violently and so frequently throughout the course of the novel. It was less sensical to me as I read, but I see now how Clerfayt could seemingly be so alluring and yet so reprehensible to Lillian. As I mentioned before, his refusal to allow the fear of death to control his life is understandably intoxicating to Lillian—she is not marked or tainted by death in his eyes despite his knowledge of her condition and he is utterly unconcerned with the future, a perspective so uncharacteristic of her fellow patients and nurses and doctors who don’t know how to think of anything but. And yet, regarding this latter quality in particular, there is a key distinction between his philosophy and Lillian’s: whereas Clerfayt lives in the present because he is seemingly not bothered by the prospect of the death that tomorrow may bring, Lillian loves and appreciates the present unlike she ever could before because her tuberculosis has forced her to be painfully aware of the immutability of death. Lillian fears death but knows she will soon meet it, and so she is resolved to live her life to the fullest; Clerfayt, on the other hand, seems to think death is not so intimidating a thing, and he does not let fear of death rule his life. This is a major schism between the two which, at face value, has led them both to lead their lives in similar manners, but which could not be much more disparate in terms of their philosophical reasonings.<br /><br />The complexity of their relationship is only exacerbated as Clerfayt truly falls in love with Lillian. In his love he begins to see more clearly his folly in being so careless in his approach to life and death, and he begins to be far more concerned for Lillian and her health, as he increasingly cannot imagine a life without her. Of course, incidentally, it is his love for her that makes him all the more unbearable to Lillian, who, though she does love him, now finds he is no different than the patients and staff at the sanatorium in his constant worrying and smothering and patronizing.<br /><br />Remarque also makes frequent allusions throughout the novel to a number of Classical (especially Greek) figures and stories. Though it is by no means a one-to-one allegory, Remarque does liken Clerfayt and Lillian’s tragic love to that of Orpheus and Eurydice. Like Orpheus, Clerfayt retrieves his love from Death and attempts to guide her back to the world of the living, only to find that he is unable to do so. Lillian also references the River Styx on a number of occasions, a story she is reminded of when looking out upon the Seine from her hotel in Paris or when feeling as though she is living a ruse, attempting to convince herself that she has been reborn when she knows that the Styx has been crossed—she owes the ferryman a life that must soon be collected. These aren’t especially unique allegories, but it did help establish a very romantic and seemingly timeless feel to the story that I found really fitting. <br /><br />This book has definitely solidified Remarque as one of my favorite authors. I felt the same way after I finished both All Quiet on the Western Front and The Road Back, but now I feel more justified after having read through more of his bibliography (and I fully intend to continue reading through his stuff because I really love his writing). The more I write about this book, the more I want to give it a 5/5, but that’s generally my tendency with most books, so I’ll keep it how I have it. Most of the scenes in this book consist of petty bourgeois characters philosophizing about life and death over expensive cocktails, wines, and multi-course meals in pretty edenic places where they have seemingly no other responsibilities. If you were to tell me this was the essence of the book beforehand, I would probably not be very interested in it, but Remarque has a real gift for making genuine and sympathetic characters—Clerfayt and Lillian, despite their decadent, high society lifestyles, are anything but unrelatable. This is of course one of the main themes of the book: what good is money and luxury if, like Lillian, you have little time remaining to enjoy it or if, like Clerfayt, you cannot escape from the horrors of your past?<br /><br />Remarque also gets bonus points for the locations in this book: the Swiss Alps, Paris, Palermo, Rome, Venice, the Riviera, Monte Carlo, etc. If you’re going to spend a whole book having your characters wax poetic and spar with platitudes, you might as well have them do it in some beautiful ass places, and Remarque delivers on that count. <br /><br />I’m now at the point in my reflection where I’m not quite sure why I’ve given this book a 4 instead of a 5, as I have no major critiques. I suppose I’ll attribute it to enjoyment: I liked this book a lot, but I didn’t just fall in love with it or find it remarkably moving, and I feel like I should reserve the 5 stars for books that either wholly captured me or which I thought were utterly brilliant. This might be what I find Remarque is so good at, though: he is not the most intellectually impressive or artistically gifted author I’ve ever read, nor is he the most gripping, but he is very much in the upper echelons of all of those categories, while also being more accessible than most other ‘classic’ authors I’ve read. And, in my opinion, he is one of the most genuine authors I’ve ever read, though I find it hard to elaborate or qualify what exactly I mean by this. I suppose I’m also giving this book a 4 to distinguish it from All Quiet on the Western Front and The Road Back, both of which are definitive 5’s for me.<br /><br />Oh, I’ve come up with one critique: the ending is very much similar to another book of Remarque’s, except that, in this case, I felt it had less emotional salience. I suppose that this is totally justified given that this ending is not meant to come as a surprise of any sort, but the fact that I’m comparing it to another far more powerful conclusion of his makes it fall a little flat. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9812059282053660916" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


